segments.text: For the date when those men were killed?
You're saying there were some men killed?
Yes, they got killed at Texas Coal Mine.
Yes, sir.
How were they killed?
Well, they say, you know, there was two mains of coal.
One, the top main and the bottom main.
And this elevator goes down to the bottom, of course.
All right.
And they claim...
Because I was a communist, they had to get some way to excuse.
They said that this man came out of the second vein, and he must have stuck his head here when the elevator was going down, and he knocked him down to the bottom and killed him.
I see.
So the elevator knocked him down to the bottom of the shaft, and that killed him?
Uh-huh.
So one man died in that accident?
One man died in that accident, yeah.
Were there any other accidents that you remember?
Well, Jose Rios was his name.
He got killed that way.
Who was it?
Jose.
Jose?
Jose Rios.
Rios?
Rios.
Rios.
R-I-O-S?
R-I-O-S. Rios.
Yes, sir.
Jose Rios.
Joe Rios.
And...
I don't remember what year it was.
No, I don't remember.
It was in the 20s, but I don't remember what year it was.
Do you remember what was the basic food that the Mexican families ate, minors?
Beans, I guess.
Beans?
Beans.
Beans and potatoes, harsh potatoes.
Harsh potatoes, beans, and rice, and such stuff as that.
Where did the miners get the food?
At the commissary.
At the commissary.
Yes.
Yeah, they kept the stuff there at the commissary.
Did they pay cash for that food, or did they just keep it on the books?
No, they kept it on the books.
And subtracted from the pay?
Every two weeks, they said, well, Augustine's got so much coming.
All right.
How about his bills?
Well, he's got a lot of bills here.
Says Augustine's got $45 coming for two weeks or half a month.
And he bought the grocers.
$30 was the grocers.
So he's got $50 left.
And that's the way it was.
He'd take home.
No, the house rent come off of that.
Did you, most of the time on payday, get some form of cash?
Yeah, a little cash was.
Well, were there any miners that were always in debt?
Oh, yes, lots of them.
Lots of them.
Never see the dime.
I see.
Yeah, lots of them.
No, it's just lots of them.
Why was that?
If there you were getting...
getting money every payday, and yet they seem to be in debt.
What was the difference between you and them?
Well, you see, I was getting $90 a month, straight time.
I see.
While they had the coal digger, he had to go in, and what he, well, he got four acres, 25 cents a car, a ton.
25 cents a car.
Uh-huh.
If he loads four cars, he made $1.
And maybe he walked a day, and maybe he put it to do, and he just left one car or two cars.
So how much will it be in a week?
Not very much.
No.
That's why they're staying dead.
They don't know how to.
I always been pretty careful myself.
If I got a dollar in my pocket, I ain't going to spend a whole dollar, no, sir.
I'm going to keep 50 cents in my pocket and spend 50 cents.
I don't know what might happen tomorrow.
I tell you, I went through this year of depression.
And I mean, I know what that is.
Yes, sir.
What did you do during the depression?
Well, I had to go back for work, and I worked 35 cents a day, cleaning toilets, whatever I could get.
You see, I had a family to support.
And I had work, and I had work for whatever I could get.
I never had what kind of work.
or how much you're going to pay me.
All I want is to wait.
When I got through that period, why didn't they want to?
And I was glad to get that.
I was doing it the first year.
You need some water?
No, thanks.
You see, I had a stroke last September, and I kind of faked my throat, this whole side, my left side.
This stroke got me.
That's the reason I got that walk I keep.
Can't put the weight on this one.
It goes to shaking.
Would you like to rest a few minutes?
No, that's all right.
I'm ready.
I'm set.
Yeah, it's all right.
Okay.
All right.
What did the women do during the day?
Who?
What did the women do during the day?
Stayed home.
Stayed home?
Stayed home.
Stayed around or what?
Just.
Well, those that had children, I guess they stayed busy with the kids.
See, they used to wash, they didn't have to wash in machines then.
They had a tub and washboard.
They had to wash on this washboard.
They had no hot water heaters.
They had a kettle.
Kettle?
Yeah, kettle.
They had to heat the water, boiling water.
And they stayed busy washing and cleaning up children.
I guess.
I don't know.
I was at my work.
I didn't know what the women do much.
I know they didn't go around because they had no automobiles.
Very few had a horse and buggy.
Very few.
I was lucky to have a horse and buggy.
Well, that's a good problem because you saved your money.
I had a horse and buggy.
Yes, I had one.
A pretty little mare.
Gray mare.
She was one of them.
What do you call that?
Peas?
Yeah, I lost my voice since I had this stroke.
You were 15 when you went into the mine.
Yeah, right, yes.
Did you know of anybody that was younger than that and was working in the mines?
No, no.
15 was about the youngest.
About the youngest.
I don't remember any kids went down to mine besides me.
Was it mostly the Mexican workers?
Yes, yeah, most of them.
Most of them, mostly, yeah.
Did they all seem to get along with each other?
Oh, yes, yes, they got along fine.
Except for Saturday nights at the dentist, when they got drunk, they had fights.
That was on the Texas Coal Company property, right?
Yes, yes.
Yeah, I guess the waitress at Johnson had the same trouble, I guess.
I never did go around.
I always stayed at my place.
Were there any other accidents like boiler explosions or anything like that?
No, no.
Do you think mining was fairly safe there?
Well, I think so.
It was about as safe as they could have it.
Well, let me ask you this.
From the time that you had your accident until the time that you quit, did you see an improvement in the mining techniques?
No, sir.
None at all.
Not at all.
And I used to drive up and down this road and into the camps, take those people to town and bring them back.
I never did it anymore, no.
So they used mainly steam power and mule power.
Yes.
Steam, the mules would start to pull the, you see those anchories, they call it, they dig it all,
half a mile long, and they'd have so many feet, they'd run what they call rooms one other way, and go so far away, they had to run back this other way.
They had to leave big, thick pillars to support, you know.
And these mules go over there and pull the cars from the end of the track like railroad, from the diggers to the cage.
And then they put it on this cage.
We call it a cage.
It's like an elevator.
They give me a signal.
Then I hushed it up.
And they had a tipple.
I hushed it into the tipple.
One cage goes down, one come up.
If the car goes down, one load comes up.
And it comes up to the tipple?
Over the tipple, they had what they called a dumper.
One man out there.
This dumper would pull that car off the cage and dump it.
Then they had to shoot that coal right into the railroad car.
Right into the railroad.
Right into the railroad car.
Was there any dirt mixed in with the coal?
Well, in some places they had little strips of dirt, but the dingo was supposed to throw that on the side.
Then when he had enough to fill up a car, he'd fill up a car in dirt.
He'd get so much for that.
About ten cents, I think, he'd give a dime to load that car in dirt.
Okay, well, how did you keep the number of cars per day?
I mean, how did each miner know how many cars?
Well, you see, each miner had his number.
He had a number.
He had a number, yeah, a bunch of checks.
Washers, brass washers, they had their number on.
For instance, I was number, say I was number 12.
My check was on marked number 12.
You was 14.
Your check was on 14.
Every time you load a car, you put that check on there.
So when it comes to the top, that dump truck pulls that check off and hangs it on the board.
All the 14s belongs to one man.
All the 12s belongs to another man.
In that way.
How many of these brass washers on the average?
Hundreds of them.
Hundreds of them.
How many a day for one miner on the average?
Well, they said they might give you, well, you wouldn't load over eight or nine cars a day.
They said they might give you 12 or 15 checks.
Might give you 15 of these washers.
And you keep them, you keep them so.
So this dumper, at good times, he comes out with a boat, has days on it.
And each day has his watches at that.
Number 12, number 10, number six, and number, everyone number now.
And of course, at the store, they knew my name, they know what was my number there.
And you number, and all the rest of them.
And the dumper would come down with them checks and turn it over to the engineer, turn it over to me.
So after I quit my agent work, I had to go and count these checks.
I'd count all these checks.
Then I'd call the office.
Then I'd call Mr. Shrimp at the office and I'd tell him, number 14, 12, 12 checks, 12 cars.
Number so-and-so, ten.
Number so-and-so, six.
Just how do you know it?
He'd put it on the book.
So you call him on the telephone?
Over the telephone from the engine room to the office over there.
And the office was at the mine?
Yeah, at the store.
Well, Augustine, did anybody ever dispute your county?
Were there ever any arguments?
Yeah, sometimes mistakes.
Sometimes...
The mistakes, maybe the double might drop a check.
Or maybe they put two checks on one.
And how were those disputes resolved?
Well, whatever the stripper said, whatever the boss said, that's not so.
You may say, Mr. Stripper, I'm too cautious.
That's what the book shows.
You can't pay for the book shows.
That's all.
There was no use to argue with them.
No use to argue?
No.
I guess whatever he said, that was all.
Did that happen very often?
No, just once in a while, just once in a while.
No, I had lots of work to do.
I had to do that.
Then I had to count the mine cars that were dumping each railroad car.
Some of them, you know, they had 60,000 capacity.
I was 80,000 capacity.
They all definitely come, you know, the railroad cars.
Someone got more capacity than that.
When I had to report so many pit cars in this, so many pit cars in this, so many pit cars in this, that the number of the car, of the railroad car, I had all that responsibility.
I see.
So you were pretty much a superintendent then?
No, I was second to the superintendent.
Okay.
How did, if you did all this, you, well, and obviously now you speak English, where did you learn English?
Out here?
I never did go to school.
You never did?
No.
You know, up in them days, we weren't allowed to go to white school.
We weren't allowed even to go to the steps, because if I walked the steps of a white school,
teacher comes, what do you want here?
Go, you ain't got no business here, get away from here.
They run me away.
So I didn't get no education.
Did the Texas Coal Company have a school?
No, no, nobody had a school, no.
I understand the Vogel Mines had a school.
No.
You don't remember that?
No, they didn't have no school.
Now his daughter,
His old man's daughter.
Gusta?
Gusta.
Gusta had school.
We had to pay for it.
Oh, I see.
We had to pay her so much for each kid.
No, we had daughters.
My daughter had school.
Nothing.
Well, with Gusta's school, where was her school?
There was a little house over there.
That was what was kept.
That was that.
They came over there.
And Mrs. Guster had a little room, a little house over there where she kept school.
And finally, we got this schoolhouse over here on the right.
For the Mexican people?
Yes.
And we had a teacher from Cameron.
She'd come here and teach.
That was paid by the state.
Do you remember what year that was?
Well...
That was after we moved here, must have been in 24, I guess.
Something like that.
1924, I betcha.
Well, before that, in Augusta School, did she service other coal mine companies?
No.
Just the Vogel mine?
No.
Kids from here went over there.
Kids from the Texas coal company went over to her school.
Yeah, gee, we paid so much.
Do you remember how much you paid?
No, I don't remember.
I didn't send mine over there, no.
So your children didn't go to school?
Not over there, no.
But they did over to your school?
Oh, yeah, you see, that top of the ridge right over there used to be got burned out.
By the mine from here, that was top of the ridge school.
But no Mexican kids over there, no.
That's about whites.
Oh, the Chapel Ridge School was for whites?
Talbert Ridge.
Talbert.
Talbert.
Talbert.
Talbert Ridge.
That's white school over there.
I see.
But no Mexicans.
No, it wasn't allowed over there at all.
But when the buses started to run, then we all got together.
That all, the Mexicans just went with them.
Mr., uh...
Uh...
Mr. Phillips' partner, Lucky, Mr. Lucky, Emmett Lucky.
Emmett Lucky?
Yeah.
Mr. Emmett Lucky was the trustee, and he kind of got me to go with him.
We went around and take lots of Mexican children to him.
I said, what's the use of this?
He said, they go to school.
I said, why?
He said, Rockdale.
They go to school in Rockdale.
There ain't going to be no more school outside the country.
All of them got to go to Rockdale.
Mine started to go to Rockdale.
Do you remember when that was?
Uh... Vera!
Uh-huh?
Do you remember when you started scooting to Rockdale?
Oh, my God.
Let's see, 1920 and 1927.
Yeah.
Well, about twenty-six or twenty-seven.
In 1927, you, uh, the Mexican... Yeah, they got, they went, they got together then, yes.
In Rockdale.
In Rockdale.
Now, before that, you had your own school, though.
Well, yeah, we had to pay that, that was in the Spanish.
Spanish school.
We had a, yeah.
Except the time that, uh, uh, Mrs. Vogel, Mrs., what was her name?
Augusta.
Mrs. Augusta.
Yeah, right.
Mrs. Augusta Vogel.
She used to teach English.
And there was this teacher came from Calvary City, but it didn't last long.
They had them all go to Rockdale.
They closed up that school over there, and all of them went to school to Rockdale.
Okay, let me be sure I have this straight, okay, Augustine.
We had a white school over at Talbot.
Talbot Ridge.
Talbot Ridge.
Uh-huh.
And then we had a Mexican school right up west of here, right?
Yeah, yes.
And that was about 1924, you said?
Oh, 1925, maybe.
And that's the one that the state paid for?
That's the teacher was coming from Denver, I guess, and the state paid her, yeah.
Okay, all right.
And then in 1927, all the students went to Rockdale.
They went to Rockdale, yeah.
I see.
But mine is starting to go over there.
I see.
Did you have a church at the Texas Coal Company?
No, we went to Rockdale Church.
You went to a Rockdale Church?
Catholic Church, yeah.
Do you remember the name of that church?
St. Joseph.
St. Joseph?
Yeah, St. Joseph.
Still St. Joseph.
Still go by that name.
So you went there every Sunday?
Every Sunday.
And, of course, you went in your buggy.
In the buggy.
We used to go in the buggy.
And after 19, after 20, we went in the car.
I bought me a Model T. Right.
Well, how did the other families get to church?
Did they walk?
Some of them walked.
Some of them, I took them.
I'd make three or four, five trips on Sunday.
I used to charge two bits apiece, you know.
And I'd load four.
I made a dollar.
Yeah.
Take them back, a dollar, bring them back.
Yeah.
Was church a pretty strong factor in the mining camps?
Well, kind of.
Not too strong, no.
They just went on Sundays then?
Yes, on Sundays, yes, on Sundays.
Do you remember any weddings?
Oh, yes, they had a lot of weddings.
Did they have them in Rockdale or did they have them at the mining?
At the camps out here, yeah.
Would the preacher or the minister come out?
Yeah, he'd come out and marry, yes.
Like myself, I was married at Texas.
You were married at the Texas Coal Company?
At Texas Coal Company, yes.
The priest and the judge came up there and married.
I was married by the judge first.
I got my license, and then our folks wanted to be married by Catholics, you know.
So I had the priest to come over from Taylor.
The priest came from Taylor to marry us.
Did you have to pay for you?
Yes, sure.
Do you remember how much you paid him?
No, I think I gave him a $5 bill.
Wow, that must have been a lot of money back then.
I gave him a $5.
He didn't charge me.
Just give him whatever I wanted to give him, I'd give him a $5 bill.
Did he do the service in Spanish or was it in English?
Spanish.
That was the priest.
The judge, Mr. Ed Gunn, was the judge that married me.
He said English.
I see.
Where did you meet your wife?
Here.
At the camp?
At the camp?
I had a buddy at the Texas Gold Company.
Was she a daughter of another miner?
No, she was a daughter.
She had a mother and two brothers.
There was two sisters and two brothers.
They didn't have a father.
I see.
They came from Mexico.
How did they end up in the mines?
Did their brothers were working?
Yeah, the brothers were working.
There was gold miners.
I see.
So the family came up without a father?
Yeah.
They were with their brothers.
I see.
There was an old lady and two girls and two boys.
And the two boys supported the two daughters and the mother?
Yeah, they were working, yeah.
Well, I said boys, that was me and grown men, but the young men.
Do you ever sit back and think about the old mining days?
No, sir.
When you just sit back and think, what do you think about?
I wish I had never seen the coal mine.
Really?
I do.
But I get to think about my legs.
Of course, I don't like to accident.
There's a lot of times I lose legs and they don't, I don't want to be in wrecks.
That could happen anywhere.
But it might happen while I was working.
I was in the mine.
That's why I lost my legs.
No, it's all right, but
I would recommend it to, I don't want my kids to go back under the ground, 100 feet on the ground.
Things got, they all learn trades today.
They're not even thinking about going in the mine.
Of course, they have a new way of mining now, you know.
Yes.
One of my boys working away at Alcoa.
Alcoa.
That's what he is.
But he's working at Alcoa.
He's not by this trip, but...
I see.
Yeah, they strip the coal now.
But we used to go down the ground and undermine it.
But they don't do that now.
No, Edward, he works at Alcoa.
He's a crane operator over there.
I see.
Does he live here?
Yeah, he lives in town.
In town.
Yeah, he lives in town.
Did he remember growing up in mines, around the mines?
No, you remember he was grown up, he was raised right by the old house, between the end and Texas Coal Company, about a quarter of a mile back there.
He was raised here.
So he wasn't, didn't, doesn't know very much about the mines.
He didn't know nothing about the mines.
Not a thing, no.
And you just assumed to be that way, I guess.
Yeah.
Yeah, he don't know nothing about mine.
No, sir.
You go to the STV, he says, I don't know.
You don't know anything?
He says, it's a hole down in the ground.
He says, that's all.
Yeah, he asked me, how do you take that mule down in the ground, Dad?
I said, they put him in this cage.
We had a sink made, and we settled on that anyway.
And then we pushed that mule, and then he closed the gate, and somebody sat here on top holding the bridle.
And then I let him down.
After downing that one, he can't do nothing.
Did they bring the mules up every night?
Well, some places they did, some places they'd keep them there till they died.
Oh, really?
Yeah, I think that was wrong.
We used to haze them every night.
No, we hushed them out every night, let them down every morning.
But after they went down, they just walked right on that gate.
After the first two, three times, usually I'd push them.
That man just walked, the driver just walked in that hole by the hauler, and that mule just walked right behind him.
They closed that gate.
Down they go.
That's all.
How did the miners and mules even get water down in the mines?
They didn't drink no water.
The miners take their jugs of water.
But the mules didn't get no water until they come out at night.
Now they eat no water until when they come out.
Did the mules last pretty long in the mines?
Yes, they lived a long time.
Pretty strong animals.
Yes, pretty strong.
They get good feed.
Feed them good.
Yeah, it's pretty good out.
Well, can you think of anything else that we've left out?
About mining?
Yeah, about the mining camps?
No, they had dances and weddings.
They had fights.
They'd get drunk on Saturday nights.
They gamble.
Some of them put it quiet.
Quiet?
Some of them were?
Yeah, quiet.
They didn't mess around with the others.
Didn't go to do games or that like that.
I mean, gambling.
Yeah.
Let me ask you this.
Any of the miners that came up from Mexico, did any of them return to Mexico?
Well, not that I know of.
Once they got here, they stayed here.
They stayed here.
Now, we had one here that he was Mr. Silver's number one man.
He's a former now for a while.
Then he got to send him off to Laredo after some hands to hire some coal diggers.
And he got so much confidence in him, he let him write checks on the Texas Coal Company.
So he went three or four times, and the last time he never did come back.
Oh, no.
He wrote a big check, got the money, and never did come back to Texas anymore.
Just today, he had never been back.
Yeah, Mr. Stevenson says, no, it was Dean.
I said, yes, sir.
You know what Joe did?
I said, no, Mr. Stevenson, what?
I knew what happened.
I said, no, Mr. Stevenson, what happened, Mr. Stevenson?
He says, that Russell give...
I checked for $350, and he never showed up anymore.
He didn't come back at all no more.
I said, what are you going to do about it now?
He said, what can we do?
We don't know what we're about.
You try to find out.
I said, I will.
I said, hide it there when I want to find out.
I never was in Mexico.
I don't know a thing about Mexico.
I never been to Laredo.
But what happened to all the mining families once the mines shut down in the 30s?
Oh, they scattered all over the country.
Some ran down in Dallas, some in Fort Worth, some in Houston.
Oh, they went all around.
Some in San Antonio.
They just scattered all over the country.
What kind of work were they doing?
I don't know.
I don't know.
They just left when the mines shut down.
Yeah, they shut down.
Some of them went to Malakoff.
To where?
Malakoff.
Malakoff?
Malakoff, Texas.
I see.
That's kind of east, I think, from here somewhere.
And that mine closed up.
And they all left there.
I had a brother that worked there a long, long time at Malakoff.
And when they closed down, he went to work for their house.
What that old company name?
Big, big outfit.
Shell?
No.
No?
No.
Exxon?
Texas.
Texas, brother.
Texas, yeah.
I see.
He went to work for Texaco.
And he still, no, he retired now.
He retired this year.
He worked 32 years with the Texaco at Fort Arthur.
I see.
And he quit this year.
He retired.
Is this a friend of yours?
My brother.
Your brother?
My brother, Jesse.
It's just me and him, just two brothers left.
He's the youngest one.
I'm the oldest one.
Yeah, me and Jesse's always left.
And they just, he's what?
He's a monocle?
